</i></p><p class="sc-ZOtfp cLnRKw pf-16_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3"><span style="color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">The diffusion of innovations theory, formulated by Everett Rogers in 1962, remains a cornerstone for understanding how new ideas and technologies spread within societies. This theory identifies five key elements that influence the diffusion process: innovation, adopters, communication channels, time, and social systems. In this blog, Dr Richard Dune will explore these elements, their significance, and best practices for implementation, particularly within regulated environments.

